<br>
Interesting comments.  <br>
In EQ PvP, four things will determine about 90% of the fights.<br>
1.)Speed.  If you can outrun your opponent, you have a huge tactical advantage, be you caster or melee.<br>
2.)Preparedness.  Buffed, or unbuffed, fm, oom, etc<br>
3.)Gear.  Resists, AC, Regeneration.  Hitting for 40 or 120 a shot<br>
4.)Level<br>
<br>
All of these things being equal, it's all about skill<br>
<br>
Does caster damage need to go back to full?  Maybe.  Tanks do have a lot of hitpoints at the higher levels, but I really don't see a lot of imbalance (assuming the four points above are all equal)<br>
<br>
Reducing melee damage in PvP is NOT a good idea.  It has a LOT more ramifications than just allowing a caster to live for a few more hits.  Damage shields and Regeneration gear both come to mind.  As it is, a level 60 monk could practically beat himself to death against a druid.  (Of course, monks are the worst solo PvP class, IMHO, because of their inability to do anything beyond beat on their target).  <br>
<br>
Yes, you could burn your entire mana bar, and not kill a tank.  I fought a enchanter for 35 minutes as a Shadow Knight.  Enchanter couldn't get me below half life, I couldn't stick close enough to hurt the enchanter, between the occasional root stick, mezes, etc.   Eventually, she grav-fluxed a little too close to a guard, and it ended badly for her.  <br>
<br>
This was one of those rare cases where neither party was unprepared (I was wearing MR rings, MR shield, 14 24 1hs [with fbss 14 21, give or take a point]), she was full life, full mana, claritied, runed (we talked about the fight for a while after she recovered her corpse).  She was a level higher than me (46 to 45)<br>
<br>
<br>
Just my 2cp<br>
<br>
